[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating file changes and coverage**\n\nI’m noticing that the diff isn’t showing the new file due to it being untracked. It seems like we don’t need to revert because the user’s scope indicates that metadata should not be edited. However, this dynamic report was modified before. I’m wondering if we should include unrelated items. The concern lies with coverage, as there's an existing test file that might not cover everything needed. Essentially, should I be checking this manually for style and test coverage?\n\n**Reviewing test class updates**\n\nThe rules suggest I should focus on improving actively only. I need to maintain a one-to-one mapping between the dynamic-access report classes and generated test class files, but that doesn’t necessarily mean increasing coverage. Since we've changed the semantics of an existing test, I’m wondering if I should avoid changing the global resource. Maybe I could use a custom classloader or alias reflection for safety. However, using MemberAccessor might involve some public API concerns, so I’m contemplating how to best structure the tests without causing issues.\n\n**Addressing test class structure**\n\nI’m considering ways to preserve instrumentation for other tests if the default delegate module is used. However, the resource class needs to be in the test source, like org_mockito.mockito_core.SelectiveMemberAccessor, which implements MemberAccessor. I ponder whether all top-level public test classes should be public, or if a support class can also be top-level. A one-to-one mapping might introduce unnecessary class files. Nesting a public static class in ReflectionMemberAccessorTest could be a better approach. I’m unsure about naming, especially with special characters like `$`, as this might affect file compatibility.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_02dd3f6334b8da5b016a2ac00cd5b48190a4ed7588167ac63e\",\"type